INSTALLATION INSTRUCTIONS IN BRIEF:

* Unpack the tarball to generate the zpomdp directory:

  tar xvfz zpomdp-0.1.tgz

* Build:

  cd zpomdp-0.1/src
  make install
  (generates zpomdp-0.1/bin/linux2/testPomdp)

* Do a test run and plot the results:

  mkdir -p zpomdp-0.1/results/
  cd zpomdp-0.1/results
  ../bin/linux2/testPomdp -i 100 hsvi ../src/problems/three_state.pomdp -- -1 1
  ../src/tools/makeplot .

* If you wish to test with one of the included RockSample problem
  instances, generate it.

  cd zpomdp-0.1/src/problems
  ./gen_RockSample_5_7
  (generates RockSample_5_7.pomdp)

==========================================================
REQUIREMENTS:

Tested operating systems: Linux kernel 2.6.x (Fedora Core 2 and 4)
Tested compilers:         gcc 3.2.2, 3.2.3

NOTE: Fedora Core users with more recent gcc versions: the easiest way
to get gcc 3.2.3 is to install the following rpms, which do not conflict
with an existing gcc 4.0 installation:
        compat-gcc-32
        compat-libstdc++-33
        compat-libstdc++-296

Build system tested with:
* GNU Make 3.80
* GNU Flex 2.5.4
* GNU Bison 2.0
* Perl 5.8.6

Optional scripts in tools directory tested with:
* gnuplot 4.0
* GNU gprof 2.15.94.0.2.2

Other dependencies:
* Depends on some gcc-specific extensions to the C language (although
  this could be fixed without too much trouble).
* Uses the C++ standard template library, including some built-in
  algorithms like std::sort().
* No dependence on external linear algebra packages or linear program solvers.

==========================================================
